    ROLE VISIBILITY (CRITICAL - AAP Section 0.7.2)
    ==============================================
    Per the assigned-folder requirements ("Agent Workspace dashboard MUST
    be visible to x_[scope]_case_agent (operationally relevant) AND to
    x_[scope]_case_manager (monitoring agents); NOT to
    x_[scope]_case_viewer unless explicitly granted"), records [8] and
    [9] are the SOLE role attachments. They bind this dashboard to BOTH
    scoped agent and manager roles. There is intentionally NO role
    attachment for:
      - x_[scope]_case_viewer (viewers have read-only on tables but no
        dashboard access by default; "unless explicitly granted" means
        a future feature, not part of this POC)
      - admin (no global-scope writes per AAP Section 0.7.2)
      - itil (no global ServiceNow role attachments per AAP)
    A user with NONE of the above roles cannot navigate to this
    dashboard from the Performance Analytics dashboard catalog.
    A user with the x_[scope]_case_agent OR x_[scope]_case_manager
    role gets the dashboard rendered with all three widgets populated
    by the underlying sys_report queries. Per AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 6
    ("Both dashboards render with synthetic data"), the demo agent
    (../seed-data/users/sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml) MUST see
    a fully-populated rendering after Update Set apply.

    LAYOUT DISCIPLINE (12-COLUMN RESPONSIVE GRID)
    =============================================
    ServiceNow's modern dashboard grid is 12-column responsive. The
    three widget records below honor this grid:
      Row 1 (lists row): two width=6 widgets at columns 1, 7.
      Row 2 (donut row): one width=12 widget at column 1.

    Position math:
      Widget 1: column=1, width=6   -> occupies columns 1-6
      Widget 2: column=7, width=6   -> occupies columns 7-12
      Widget 3: column=1, width=12  -> occupies columns 1-12

    Row math (each widget is height=4):
      Widget 1, 2: row=1 -> occupies rows 1-4
      Widget 3:    row=5 -> occupies rows 5-8

    On mobile/tablet viewports (below ~768px), ServiceNow auto-stacks
    widgets vertically; the column/width values become collapsed to a
    single-column layout. The dashboard remains usable on a phone.

    No widget overlaps any other widget. The total grid usage is
    8 row-units tall and 12 columns wide on desktop.

    ORDER FIELDS
    ============
    The pa_dashboards record carries `<order>100</order>` so this
    dashboard appears BEFORE the Manager View dashboard
    (`<order>200</order>`) when a user holds both case_agent and
    case_manager roles. This gives a natural reading order: agent
    dashboard first (daily-driver), manager dashboard second
    (operational-review). The manager dashboard's order=200 is
    documented in ../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_[scope]_manager_view.xml
    (line 459).

    The pa_tab record carries `<order>1</order>` because there is
    exactly one tab on this dashboard. If future iterations add a
    second tab, that tab would carry `<order>2</order>`.

    The pa_m2m_dashboard_tabs record carries `<order>1</order>` for
    its position in the dashboard's tab list (left-most tab).

    The pa_dashboard_widgets records carry order values 10, 20, 30
    (left-to-right, top-to-bottom across the grid). These order values
    do NOT affect grid placement (column/row/width/height do that);
    they affect tab-key navigation order and accessibility-tool reading
    order. The 10/20/30 spacing leaves room for future widgets to be
    inserted (e.g., 15) without renumbering.

    ICON
    ====
    The pa_dashboards `<icon>fa-tasks</icon>` field references the
    FontAwesome `fa-tasks` glyph. This icon is decorative only - it
    appears next to the dashboard title in the Performance Analytics
    dashboard catalog. The fa-tasks glyph (a checklist/clipboard icon)
    visually evokes "agent's work queue", distinguishing this dashboard
    from the Manager View (which uses fa-line-chart for "managerial
    KPIs"). If the target PDI release ships a different FontAwesome
    version that has renamed `fa-tasks`, the dashboard catalog will
    fall back to a default icon; the dashboard itself remains fully
    functional.

    AUDIT TIMESTAMPS
    ================
    All `<sys_created_on>` and `<sys_updated_on>` fields use the
    fixed value `2025-01-01 00:00:00` to make this Update Set XML
    deterministically re-importable. ServiceNow ignores these values
    on import (the platform stamps the actual import timestamp on
    each row) but having a fixed value here keeps the file byte-for-
    byte stable across re-generation runs. This matches the convention
    used by sibling reports, ACLs, the manager_view dashboard, and
    other artifacts in this scoped application.

    The `<sys_created_by>` and `<sys_updated_by>` fields use `admin`
    because the Update Set is exported by an admin user on the
    development PDI; on apply, the platform overrides these with
    the actual importing user. This too matches sibling artifacts.

    XML WELL-FORMEDNESS
    ===================
    Per AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7 (Update Set integrity) and the
    assigned-folder requirements, this file MUST parse cleanly with
    `xmllint -noout`. The XML is rooted at `<unload>` with the
    required `unload_date` attribute, contains exactly 9 child record
    elements, uses 4-space indentation, employs lowercase booleans
    (`true`/`false`), and closes every opened tag. No embedded
    `<![CDATA[` blocks are needed because none of the field values
    contain XML special characters.

    Element ordering within each record: alphabetical (per ServiceNow's
    standard export convention, matching the sibling manager_view
    dashboard, the sibling reports, and other artifacts in this project).

